sql:
SELECT AVG(ur.liking) AS avg_liking_rating
FROM user_ratings ur
WHERE ur.liking > 80;

external_knowledge:
- "harmoniously loved" refers to tracks with an average liking greater than 90;
- "resonating with high consonance and valence" refers to tracks with average consonance and valence greater than 90;
- "latest tracks" refers to the most recent versions of the tracks.

- "musical connoisseurs" refers to users who have the highest average ratings across multiple musical attributes;
- "appreciation score" is the average of the user's ratings for liking, consonance, valence, and excitement;
- "emotional depth" is represented by the valence (positive or negative emotion);
- "harmony" is represented by the consonance level;
- "positivity" is also represented by the valence;
- "energy" is represented by the excitement level.

sql:
SELECT artist, AVG(liking) AS average_liking
FROM music_tracks
GROUP BY artist;

external_knowledge:
- Tracks longer than 3 minutes are considered to have more substance and depth;
- High average liking (greater than 70) indicates strong user satisfaction;
- High average consonance (greater than 60) suggests a pleasant and harmonious listening experience;
- A high number of total ratings (more than 10) indicates that the track has been evaluated by a significant number of listeners;
- The query filters genres to those with more than 5 tracks meeting the criteria, ensuring a robust and diverse selection.

- "Stand out the most" refers to having the highest absolute difference in average ratings;
- "How much listeners like them" refers to the average liking rating;
- "How harmonious they sound" refers to the average consonance rating.

sql:
SELECT MAX(average_valence) AS highest_average_valence
FROM (
    SELECT AVG(valence) AS average_valence
    FROM music_tracks
    GROUP BY genre
);

external_knowledge:
- "most musically appreciated genre" refers to the genre with the highest average user liking;
- "considering the most recent release" means the query focuses on the latest track released in each genre;
- "user liking" is a measure of how much users enjoy the track;
- "tempo" is the speed or pace of the track;
- "sound quality" refers to the clarity and fidelity of the audio;
- "number of edited versions" indicates how many times the track has been edited or remixed.

- "Overall rating" is the sum of the average liking, consonance, valence, and excitement levels for each track;
- "Edited" tracks are those that have been modified in some way;
- "Version date" is the date when a specific version of the track was created.

- 'Edited' tracks are those that have been modified or revised after their initial release;
- 'Liking' is a user's overall satisfaction or enjoyment of the track;
- 'Top 10 most liked' refers to the tracks with the highest average liking scores;
- 'Female users aged 20 to 40' refers to the demographic of users who provided the ratings;
- 'Preferred Rock genre' indicates that the users have a preference for Rock music.

- 'Most highly-rated' refers to the track with the highest average liking score;
- 'Specific user' refers to the user with user_id = 0;
- 'First half of 2023' refers to the period between January 1, 2023, and June 1, 2023.

- "sprouted multiple edited versions" refers to tracks that have more than one edited version;
- "cherished by the audience" refers to tracks that have user ratings;
- "average rating" is the average of user likings for a track.

- "Connoisseurs of recent, highly ornamented music" refers to users who have an average liking score greater than 50 and prefer tracks with an ornamentation score greater than 50;
- "Resonates with their tastes" means the music tracks match the users' preferred genres and artists;
- "Recent" refers to tracks released after January 1, 2020.
